				<span class="comment_time">// Aug 31, 2012 at 11:02 am</span>
			</p>
			<div class="entry">
				<p>Frame! Fortune! Power! Sexy specimins of the whatever gender you prefer worshiping you from afar and up close!  If you are looking for these and more &#8230; don&#8217;t become a web development blogger!</p>
<p>Seriously, though: if you are interested in how the <code>Matrix</code> filter, you should also read another article on this site, <a href="http://www.useragentman.com/blog/2011/01/07/css3-matrix-transform-for-the-mathematically-challenged/" rel="nofollow">The CSS3 matrix() Transform for the Mathematically Challenged</a>.  After reading this keep in mind that:</p>
<p><code>matrix(a, b, c, d, e, f)</code> ≈ <code>progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.Matrix(<br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;M11=a,M12=b,M21=c,M22=d,SizingMethod='auto expand');</code></p>
<p>Where ≈ means &#8220;kind of equivalent to&#8221;.  The Matrix filter doesn&#8217;t have a constant transform origin, and you will have to compensate by moving the resultant transform using either <code>margin-top</code> and <code>margin-left</code> or <code>top</code> and <code>left</code>.  It is a little fiddly, but once you get used to the gotchas of the Matrix filter, it really makes a difference in IE < 9.
</p>
 
								
			</div>
                        <div class="clearboth"></div>
