				<strong><span class='eg-image' style='float:right; margin-left:10px; display:block; width:80px' ><a rel='external nofollow' href='http://www.useragentman.com'><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/9a579fa051b35266678735c8a3751771?s=80&#038;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.useragentman.com%2Fimages%2Funknown.png&#038;r=g' srcset='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/9a579fa051b35266678735c8a3751771?s=160&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.useragentman.com%2Fimages%2Funknown.png&amp;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /></a></span><a href='http://www.useragentman.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>zoltan</a> </strong>
				<span class="comment_time">// Oct 15, 2012 at 8:28 pm</span>
			</p>
			<div class="entry">
				<p>@manfer: It is best to look at <a href="http://www.useragentman.com/shared/js/cssSandpaper.js" rel="nofollow">the source code of cssSandpaper</a>, which is what the IE Transform Translator uses to do the heavy lifting.  The interesting bits are in the functions <code>getTransformedDimensions</code>, <code>getIEMatrixOffsets</code> which is what the main function <code>setMatrixFilter</code> uses.  Searching for these methods in the code will give you the information you need.  </p>
<p>I do understand these calculations are not obvious &#8230; it&#8217;s why Zoe and I created the IE Transform Translator in the first place.  I can&#8217;t do these calculations in my head either.  :-)</p>
 
								
			</div>
                        <div class="clearboth"></div>
		</li>
                		
